window.docContents[52].resolve({"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Forthcoming-in-mathlib":{"contents":"The nodes below are informal statements of results that are the subject of open mathlib pull\nrequests (the t-number-theory queue, as of June 2026). Each carries a pr_url pointing at the\nlive PR and no (lean := …) reference: the declarations are not yet in mathlib\nv4.30.0-rc2. They connect into the dependency graph through the Mathlib-backed nodes of this\nchapter via {uses} edges. Statements should be re-pointed to (lean := …) once the\ncorresponding PR merges.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Algebraic Number Theory","header":"3.14. Forthcoming in mathlib","id":"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Forthcoming-in-mathlib"},"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Galois-extensions-and-the-fundamental-theorem/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Galois-extensions-and-the-fundamental-theorem":{"contents":"\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Class Field Theory and Galois Theory","header":"4.1. Galois extensions and the fundamental theorem","id":"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Galois-extensions-and-the-fundamental-theorem/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Galois-extensions-and-the-fundamental-theorem"},"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT":{"contents":"The ClassFieldTheory Clay-school project (Buzzard et al.) develops a cohomological route to local\nclass field theory. The group- and Tate-cohomology foundations and the abstract Tate-theorem\nmachinery — including the reciprocity isomorphism attached to a finite class formation — are\nsorry-free; the analytic input computing the Herbrand quotient of the local unit group, and hence\nthe construction of the global local-field class formation and the explicit local reciprocity map,\nare still in progress. The nodes below are informal; each links to its exact source declaration and\nstates whether that declaration is currently sorry-free.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Class Field Theory and Galois Theory","header":"4.6. Group cohomology, Tate cohomology, Herbrand quotients, and local CFT","id":"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT"},"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Forthcoming-in-mathlib--The-Gelfond-Schneider-Theorem":{"contents":"(Gelfond–Schneider theorem, Hilbert's seventh problem.) Let  be algebraic numbers\n() with , , and .\nThen any value of\n\nis transcendental. In particular  (the Gelfond–Schneider constant) and\n are transcendental.The proof is the auxiliary-function method: assuming  algebraic, one builds an\nauxiliary polynomial in  and  that vanishes to high order at many\ninteger points, then derives a contradiction between an arithmetic lower bound on its nonzero\nderivatives and an analytic upper bound — the same tension between good rational/algebraic\napproximation and transcendence that drives Liouville's theorem\n(), with the pigeonhole construction of the auxiliary function\nresting on Diophantine approximation (). PR #35735 formalises the analytic\ncore (non-vanishing and lower bounds for the Gelfond–Schneider auxiliary function; companion PRs\n#33050, #35743, #35744 supply further analytic lemmas).\nIn review — mathlib PR #35735.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Diophantine Equations and Transcendence\u0009Forthcoming in mathlib","header":"9.8.1. The Gelfond-Schneider Theorem","id":"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Forthcoming-in-mathlib--The-Gelfond-Schneider-Theorem"},"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--Forthcoming-in-mathlib":{"contents":"The nodes below are informal statements of results that are the subject of open mathlib pull\nrequests (the t-number-theory queue). Each carries a pr_url pointing at the live PR and no\n(lean := …) reference: the declarations are not yet in mathlib v4.30.0-rc2. They connect into the\ndependency graph through the Mathlib-backed -adic nodes of this chapter via {uses} edges, and\nshould be re-pointed to (lean := …) once the corresponding PR merges.\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009p-adic and Adic Spaces","header":"5.16. Forthcoming in mathlib","id":"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--Forthcoming-in-mathlib"}});